## 6. Design Implications

The site context suggests that EDEN’s design strategy can be interpreted through five main ideas:

### 6.1 Creating a private garden residence in the city

Although EDEN is close to Orchard Road and Singapore’s commercial center, the project creates a residential atmosphere of retreat. The tower is designed as a vertical garden residence rather than a typical urban apartment block.

### 6.2 Responding to Singapore’s tropical climate

The building uses deep balconies, planting, facade depth, and textured concrete walls to respond to strong sunlight, heat, humidity, and the need for shaded outdoor space.

### 6.3 Turning each apartment into a full-floor garden home

Unlike many high-rise apartments that divide each floor into multiple units, EDEN gives each apartment an entire floor. This allows the plan to open toward several directions and makes the garden balconies feel like part of a private house.

### 6.4 Filtering privacy through vegetation

The surrounding area contains many other high-rise residential buildings. EDEN uses tropical planting as a visual filter to create privacy while still maintaining openness and outward views.

### 6.5 Extending Singapore’s “City in a Garden” idea vertically

The project can be read as a vertical interpretation of Singapore’s garden-city identity. Greenery is not only placed at ground level but is lifted upward into every residential floor.

